Implement the private `do_reach/5` function.

`do_reach/5` is the recursive workhorse behind `reach_path/3`; it performs a
depth-first search over the forward adjacency map (`out_edges`) looking for a
path from `current` to `target`. Its arguments are
`(out_edges, current, target, visited, acc)` where `visited` is a `MapSet` of
vertices already on the current search stack and `acc` is the reversed list of
vertices visited so far (nearest vertex first, i.e. the current path built up in
reverse).

It must behave as follows:

  * If `current == target`, the search has arrived: return the path from the
    original start to `target` in forward order — that is, `[current | acc]`
    reversed with `Enum.reverse/1`, yielding `[start, ..., target]`.
  * Otherwise, if `current` is already a member of `visited`, this branch has
    looped back on itself without reaching `target`; return `nil`.
  * Otherwise, add `current` to `visited`, then look up its successors in
    `out_edges` (defaulting to an empty `MapSet` when absent), convert them to a
    list, and sort them (so the search is deterministic). Recurse into each
    neighbour with `current` prepended to `acc`, using `Enum.find_value/2` so the
    first neighbour that yields a non-`nil` path short-circuits and that path is
    returned; if no neighbour reaches `target`, `Enum.find_value/2` returns `nil`.

